article.description:
Sheryl Swoopes scored 15 points and led the host Houston Comets to a 62-44 win over the San Antonio Silver Stars on
Saturday.
article.headline: 12-1 first-half run powers Houston to go 3-0 vs. Stars
article.linkText: Swoopes, Snow, Arcain lead Comets' rout of Stars
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes scored 15 points and led the
Houston Comets to a 62-44 win over the San Antonio Silver Stars on
Saturday.

Michelle Snow added 13 points and a game-high 12 rebounds,
helping the Comets improve to 3-0 this season against the
struggling Silver Stars.

Janeth Arcain hit four of her 12 shots and was 6-for-6 from the
free-throw line, finishing with 14 points for the Comets. Houston
(6-5) won back-to-back games -- both over San Antonio -- for the
first time since taking two straight on May 29 and June 4.

"I thought this was just a great win for us," Swoopes said.
"It's hard to beat the same team three times, especially since we
just played them a week ago. I was amazed at how well we played
together, especially on the defensive side of the ball."

Katie Feenstra came off the bench and scored a team-high 13
points for the Silver Stars (3-11), who scored a franchise low and
fell to 0-7 against teams from the Western Conference. San Antonio
is 1-7 on the road.

"Offensively, we didn't play well at all," San Antonio coach
Dan Hughes said. "We didn't value the ball, we didn't take care of
it and we didn't execute. I don't remember the last team a starting
lineup combined for 18 points. It was just one of those games that
we didn't go to the basket and get any chances."

The Comets used a 12-1 run in the middle of the first half to
take control. Dominique Canty started the run with a layup and
Arcain hit a 16-foot jumper just over four minutes later to make it
25-7. Swoopes scored four points during that run and finished with
a game-high 13 points at the break.

San Antonio committed 11 turnovers and made just seven of its 24
first-half shots.

Houston led 37-20 at halftime, but San Antonio cut the lead to
10 on a layup by Shyra Ely with 6:31 left in the game.

Snow helped the Comets to a season-high 36 rebounds in the game.
The Comets had 35 rebounds in a home win over Minnesota on May 22.

"We worked on a lot of rebounding drills all week and I think
it showed," Snow said. "As a team we stepped up and even the
guards were getting in on the act by grabbing a few long
rebounds."
